# GoSteady firmware Kconfig — project-local symbols.
#
# Imports the standard Zephyr Kconfig tree first, then adds GoSteady-
# specific switches. Set values in prj.conf (always-on bench config)
# or in an overlay like prj_field.conf (deployment).

mainmenu "GoSteady firmware configuration"

source "Kconfig.zephyr"

menu "GoSteady"

config GOSTEADY_FIELD_MODE
	bool "Build for deployment (field) mode"
	default n
	help
	  When enabled, the firmware is built for unattended deployment
	  operation per the M10.5 spec:

	    - SW0 button handler is disabled (no manual session start).
	    - uart1 dump channel is not started (and with it, the BLE NUS
	      tunnel that piggybacks on uart1 from the bridge — `START`
	      from capture.html no longer routes to a session-start path).
	    - LED heartbeat tick (purple blink) is silenced. Recording-
	      time green LED is also silenced. Only the M12.1e pre-
	      activation blue LED remains in deployment.
	    - Heartbeat log line on uart0 is silenced.
	    - Auto-start uses FIELD_PREWALK (subject_id="deployed",
	      course_id="field", etc.) instead of the bench placeholders;
	      patient attribution is cloud-side per portal contract.

	  Pure motion-driven autonomous capture: ADXL367 wake-on-motion
	  → BMI270 confirmation → session → M9-motion-gate auto-stop.

	  Default off so bench builds keep all existing tooling. Build
	  the deployment image with:

	    west build -b thingy91x/nrf9151/ns -- -DEXTRA_CONF_FILE=prj_field.conf

config GOSTEADY_CLOUD_ENABLE
	bool "Enable AWS IoT MQTT/TLS cloud bring-up"
	default n
	help
	  When enabled, src/cloud.c is compiled and main() spawns the
	  one-shot heartbeat publisher worker on boot. The publisher
	  waits for cellular registration + network time, opens an MQTT/
	  TLS connection to AWS IoT Core (cert at sec_tag 201, provisioned
	  via tools/flash_cert.py), publishes one heartbeat to
	  gs/{client_id}/heartbeat, and exits.

	  Default off so bench data-collection runs (M8 captures via
	  capture.html / pull_sessions.py) are undisturbed by cellular
	  activity at boot. The ~78 KB of aws_iot + mqtt_helper + mbedTLS
	  + TLS sockets that come along with this Kconfig are also paid
	  for only in builds that opt in.

	  Three build configurations:

	    west build                                              # bench, no cloud — default M8 data-collection workflow
	    west build -- -DEXTRA_CONF_FILE=prj_cloud.conf          # bench + cloud — for M12.1c.1+ on-device cloud testing
	    west build -- -DEXTRA_CONF_FILE=prj_field.conf          # deployment — FIELD_MODE + cloud

	  prj_field.conf includes the cloud block inline so deployment
	  builds need only the single overlay; prj_cloud.conf is the
	  same block factored out for bench cloud-testing without
	  pulling in FIELD_MODE.

config GOSTEADY_CLOUD_SHADOW_BENCH_CHECK
	bool "M12.1e.1 Shadow GET + UPDATE round-trip bench check"
	depends on GOSTEADY_CLOUD_ENABLE
	default n
	help
	  When enabled, src/cloud.c spawns a one-shot worker that fires
	  ~30 s after boot, takes the aws_iot mutex, and runs an explicit
	  Shadow GET followed by a Shadow UPDATE against the bench Thing's
	  shadow document. Outcome is logged loudly to uart0:

	    "M12.1e.1 SHADOW BENCH CHECK: PASS"  → M12.1e.2 can use Shadow.
	    "M12.1e.1 SHADOW BENCH CHECK: FAIL"  → fall back to MQTT-retained
	                                            activate cmd per §C.4.4.

	  Closes the open coord-doc question §C.5.1 ("does the NCS 3.2.4
	  aws_iot lib's Shadow surface work end-to-end on this build?").

	  Bench-only — keep off for shipping deployment builds. The Shadow
	  topic SUBSCRIBE Kconfigs (CONFIG_AWS_IOT_TOPIC_GET_ACCEPTED_SUBSCRIBE
	  etc.) need to be y when this is y, plus the per-thing IoT policy
	  must permit shadow MQTT topics — both granted by the cloud team
	  in coord §C6.1 (2026-04-28).

config GOSTEADY_FORENSICS_STRESS
	bool "Compile in CRASH / STALL stress-test commands"
	depends on GOSTEADY_FORENSICS_ENABLE
	default n
	help
	  Adds two debug commands to the uart1 dump channel:

	    CRASH    NULL-derefs to trigger a HardFault. Validates that
	             k_sys_fatal_error_handler captures the ESF, persists
	             fault_count + last_fault to the crash_forensics
	             partition, and reboots cleanly.

	    STALL    Sets a flag that causes the WDT supervisor to stop
	             feeding the watchdog. Hardware watchdog fires ~60 s
	             later. Validates that hwinfo reports RESET_WATCHDOG
	             on next boot and that watchdog_hits increments.

	  Bench-only — never enable for a real deployment build. Used to
	  validate the M10.7.3 crash-forensics path before site-survey ship
	  (per the M10.5 risk table) and again on each shipping unit during
	  bring-up. Off by default.

config GOSTEADY_FORENSICS_ENABLE
	bool "Enable crash forensics + watchdog (M10.7.3)"
	default n
	select WATCHDOG
	select HWINFO
	select REBOOT
	help
	  When enabled, src/forensics.c is compiled and gosteady_forensics_init()
	  is called from main(). Captures reset cause via hwinfo at every boot,
	  persists boot_count + fault_count + watchdog_hits to the
	  `crash_forensics` external-flash partition (M10.7.1), and overrides
	  the kernel's k_sys_fatal_error_handler to record the fault frame
	  before the default reboot fires.

	  Also starts a single-channel hardware watchdog (60 s timeout) kicked
	  from a dedicated supervisor thread at 20 s cadence. If the kernel
	  hangs for longer than the timeout the WDT triggers a reset, which
	  the next boot reads back via hwinfo and increments watchdog_hits.

	  Default off so bench data-collection runs aren't disturbed by the
	  watchdog (which would fire if a debugger pauses the CPU mid-run
	  beyond CONFIG_WDT_DISABLE_AT_BOOT semantics, or if a long-running
	  test stalls the supervisor). Cloud + field builds opt in.

endmenu
